# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: time-sensitive-networking
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] IEEE 802.1Qat and 802.1Qav amendments have been incorporated to the base IEEE 802.1Q-2011 document, which specifies the operation of Media Access Control (MAC) Bridges and Virtual Bridged Local Area Networks.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] AVB was initially developed by the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) Audio Video Bridging task group of the IEEE 802.1 standards committee.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] In November 2012, Audio Video Bridging task group was renamed to Time-Sensitive Networking task group to reflect the expanded scope of its work, which is to "provide the specifications that will allow time-synchronized low latency streaming services through IEEE 802 networks".
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] Further standardization efforts are ongoing in IEEE 802.1 TSN task group.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] To help ensure interoperability between devices that implement the AVB and TSN standards, the AVnu Alliance develops device certification for the automotive, consumer, and professional audio and video markets.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] Analog audio-video (AV) equipment historically used one-way, single-purpose, point-to-point connections.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] Even digital AV standards, such as S/PDIF for audio and the serial digital interface (SDI) for video, retain these properties.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] This connection model results in large masses of cables, especially in professional applications and high-end audio.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] Attempts to solve these problems were based on multi-point network topologies, such as IEEE 1394 (FireWire), and included adaptation of standard switched computer network technologies such as Audio over Ethernet and Audio over IP.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] Professional, home, and automotive AV solutions came to use specialized protocols that do not interoperate with each other or standard IT protocols, while standard computer networks did not provide tight quality of service with strict timing and predictable or bounded latency.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] To overcome these limitations, Audio Video Bridging networks transmit multiple audiovisual streams through standard Ethernet switches (i.e.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] *MAC bridges*) connected in a hierarchical tree topology.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] AVB includes layer 2 protocols to reserve connection bandwidth and prioritise network traffic, which guarantee precise sync clock and low transmission latency for each stream.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] Worst-case delay, including source and destination buffering, is required to be low and deterministic: the user-interface delay shall be around 50 ms, so that the pressing of a button and the resulting action are perceived as happening instantly, and 2 ms for live performance or studio work.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] Audio Video Bridging is implemented as a switched Ethernet network that works by reserving a fraction of the available Ethernet for AV traffic.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] The IEEE 802.1BA is an umbrella standard for these three principal technologies, which defines application-specific configurations and operation procedures for devices in switched audio-video networks.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] AVB traffic is replicated in a multicast manner, with one talker (stream initiator) and multiple listeners.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] AVB packets are sent at regular intervals in the allocated time slots, preventing collisions for AV traffic.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] AVB guarantees a latency of 2 ms for Class A traffic and 50 ms for Class B traffic over a maximum of 7 hops, with a transmission period of 125 μs for Class A and 250 μs for Class B traffic.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] An IEEE 802.1AS network timing domain includes all devices that communicate using the gPTP protocol.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] The grandmaster is a device chosen as the reference clock; the 802.1BA specification requires every talker and network bridge to be grandmaster capable.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] 802.3 link management and 802.1AS link delay measurement protocols calculate the round-trip delay to the AVB endpoint; this needs to be better than worst-case wire delay from the 802.1AS peer delay algorithm.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] Higher-level protocols may use 802.1AS clock information to set the exact presentation time for each AV stream.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] IEEE Std 1722-2011 for a Layer 2 Audio Video Transport Protocol (AVTP) defines details for transmitting IEEE 1394/IEC 61883 streams and other AV formats, setting the presentation time for each AV stream, and manage latencies from worst case delay calculated by the gPTP protocol.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] IEEE Std 1722.1-2013 is a standard that provides AVB discovery, enumeration, connection management, and control (AVDECC) of devices using IEEE Std 1722-2011.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] AVDECC defines operations to discover device addition and removal, retrieve device entity model, connect and disconnect streams, manage device and connection status, and remote control devices.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] Higher-layer services can improve synchronisation and latency of media transmission by mapping the AVB Stream ID to internal stream identifiers and basing internal timestamps on gPTP master clock.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] AES67 is based on standard RTP over UDP/IP and IEEE 1588 Precision Time Protocol (PTPv2) for timing; interoperability with AVB/TSN can be achieved by linking IEEE 802.1AS timing information to AES67 PTPv2 payload data.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] AES67 implementation with AVB interoperability has been demoed at InfoComm 2016.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] In 2018, the Avnu Alliance announced the Milan initiative to promote interoperability of AVB devices and provide product certification and testing.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] Redundancy is provided with two independent logical networks for every endpoint and a seamless switchover mechanism.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] The IETF Deterministic Networking (DetNet) Working Group is working to define deterministic data paths with bounds on latency, loss, and packet delay variation (jitter), and high reliability.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] DetNet shall operate over both Layer 2 bridged segments and Layer 3 routed segments, relying on interoperability with AVB/TSN switches when possible.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] The stated goal is to enable geographically distributed, campus- or enterprise-wide Intranet for content delivery with bounded low latency (10-15 ms).
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] A single network shall handle both A/V and IT traffic, with Layer 3 routing on top of AVB QoS networks to enable sharing content between Layer 2 AVB segments, and provide IntServ and DiffServ integration with AVB where possible.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] Unused reserved bandwidth shall be released for best-effort traffic.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] The protocol stack shall have Plug-and-play capabilities from top to bottom to reduce manual setup and administration, allow quick changes of network devices and network topology.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] The work on A/V streaming started at the IEEE 802.3re 'Residential Ethernet' study group in July 2004.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/audio-video-bridging] In November 2005, it was moved to the IEEE 802.1 committee responsible for cross-network bridging standards.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] Portions of the network that are VLAN-aware (i.e., IEEE 802.1Q conformant) can include VLAN tags.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] When a frame enters the VLAN-aware portion of the network, a tag is added to represent the VLAN membership.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] Each frame must be distinguishable as being within exactly one VLAN.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] A frame in the VLAN-aware portion of the network that does not contain a VLAN tag is assumed to be flowing on the **native VLAN**.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] The standard was developed by IEEE 802.1, a working group of the IEEE 802 standards committee, and continues to be actively revised with notable amendments including IEEE 802.1ad, IEEE 802.1ak and IEEE 802.1s.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] The 802.1Q-2014 revision incorporated the IEEE 802.1D-2004 standard, which originally defined bridging and Spanning Tree Protocol.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] 802.1Q adds a 32-bit field between the source MAC address and the EtherType fields of the original frame.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] Under 802.1Q, the maximum frame size is extended from 1,518 bytes to 1,522 bytes.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] The minimum frame size remains 64 bytes, but a bridge may extend the minimum frame size from 64 to 68 bytes on transmission.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] This allows a tag to be popped without needing additional padding.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] Two bytes are used for the tag protocol identifier (TPID), the other two bytes for tag control information (TCI).
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] The TCI field is further divided into PCP, DEI, and VID.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] in order to identify the frame as an IEEE 802.1Q-tagged frame.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] This field is located at the same position as the EtherType field in untagged frames, and is thus used to distinguish the frame from untagged frames.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] Different PCP values can be used to prioritize different classes of traffic.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] ) May be used separately or in conjunction with PCP to indicate frames eligible to be dropped in the presence of congestion.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] A 12-bit field specifying the VLAN to which the frame belongs.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] All other values may be used as VLAN identifiers, allowing up to 4,094 VLANs.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] The VID value 0xFFF is reserved for implementation use; it must not be configured or transmitted.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] 0xFFF can be used to indicate a wildcard match in management operations or filtering database entries.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] In other words, the VLAN tag follows the SNAP header.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] For 802.3 frames in LLC-SNAP format, the order is opposite; the VLAN tag is placed *before* the LLC-SNAP header.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] Because inserting the VLAN tag changes the frame, 802.1Q encapsulation forces a recalculation of the original frame check sequence field in the Ethernet trailer.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] The IEEE 802.3ac standard increased the maximum Ethernet frame size from 1518 bytes to 1522 bytes to accommodate the four-byte VLAN tag.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] Some network devices that do not support the larger frame size will process these frames successfully but may report them as *baby giant* anomalies.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] IEEE 802.1ad introduced the concept of double tagging.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] Double tagging can be useful for Internet service providers (ISPs), allowing them to use their VLANs internally while carrying traffic from clients that is already VLAN tagged.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] The outer (next to the source MAC and representing ISP VLAN) S-TAG (service tag) comes first, followed by the inner C-TAG (customer tag).
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] In such cases, 802.1ad specifies a TPID of 0x88a8 for service-provider outer S-TAG.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] IEEE 802.1Q defines the Multiple VLAN Registration Protocol (MVRP), an application of the Multiple Registration Protocol, allowing bridges to negotiate the set of VLANs to be used over a specific link.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] MVRP replaced the slower GARP VLAN Registration Protocol (GVRP) in 2007 with the IEEE 802.1ak-2007 amendment.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802-1q] The 2003 revision of the standard was the first to include the Multiple Spanning Tree Protocol (MSTP), which was originally defined in IEEE 802.1s.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802] The IEEE 802 LAN/MAN Standards Committee makes current standards freely available, after a six-month delay, through their Get IEEE 802.1 program.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/ieee-802] Other recent 802.1 standards are available through the IEEE for a fee.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is also used in simulation to mean that the simulation's clock runs at the same speed as a real clock.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Real-time responses are often understood to be in the order of milliseconds, and sometimes microseconds.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] A system not specified as operating in real time cannot usually *guarantee* a response within any timeframe, although *typical* or *expected* response times may be given.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Real-time processing *fails* if not completed within a specified deadline relative to an event; deadlines must always be met, regardless of system load.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] A real-time system has been described as one which "controls an environment by receiving data, processing them, and returning the results sufficiently quickly to affect the environment at that time".
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is used in process control and enterprise systems to mean "without significant delay".
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Real-time software may use one or more of the following: synchronous programming languages, real-time operating systems (RTOSes), and real-time networks.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Each of these provides essential frameworks on which to build a real-time software application.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Systems used for many safety-critical applications must be real-time, such as for control of fly-by-wire aircraft, or anti-lock brakes, both of which demand immediate and accurate mechanical response.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] The term *real-time* derives from its use in early simulation, where a real-world process is simulated at a rate which matched that of the real process (now called real-time simulation to avoid ambiguity).
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Analog computers, most often, were capable of simulating at a much faster pace than real-time, a situation that could be just as dangerous as a slow simulation if it were not also recognized and accounted for.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Minicomputers, particularly from the 1970s onwards, when built into dedicated embedded systems such as DOG (digital on-screen graphic) scanners, increased the need for low-latency priority-driven responses to important interactions with incoming data.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Operating systems such as Data General's RDOS (Real-Time Disk Operating System) and RTOS with background and foreground scheduling as well as Digital Equipment Corporation's RT-11 date from this era.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Background-foreground scheduling allowed low-priority tasks CPU time when no foreground task needed to execute, and gave absolute priority within the foreground to threads/tasks with the highest priority.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Real-time operating systems would also be used for time-sharing multiuser duties.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] For example, Data General Business Basic could run in the foreground or background of RDOS and would introduce additional elements to the scheduling algorithm to make it more appropriate for people interacting via dumb terminals.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Early personal computers were sometimes used for real-time computing.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] The possibility of deactivating other interrupts allowed for hard-coded loops with defined timing, and the low interrupt latency allowed the implementation of a real-time operating system, giving the user interface and the disk drives lower priority than the real-time thread.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] However, several coding libraries exist that offer real-time capabilities in a high-level language on a variety of operating systems, for example, Real-time Java.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Later microprocessors such as the Motorola 68000 and subsequent family members (68010, 68020, ColdFire, etc.) also became popular with manufacturers of industrial control systems.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] This application area is one where real-time control offers genuine advantages in terms of process performance and safety.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] A system is said to be *real-time* if the total correctness of an operation depends not only upon its logical correctness, but also upon the time in which it is performed.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Thus, the goal of a *hard real-time system* is to ensure that all deadlines are met, but for *soft real-time systems* the goal becomes meeting a certain subset of deadlines in order to optimize some application-specific criteria.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] The particular criteria optimized depend on the application, but some typical examples include maximizing the number of deadlines met, minimizing the lateness of tasks and maximizing the number of high-priority tasks meeting their deadlines.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] In the context of multitasking systems the scheduling policy is normally priority driven (pre-emptive schedulers).
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] In some situations, these can guarantee hard real-time performance (for instance, if the set of tasks and their priorities is known in advance).
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] There are other hard real-time schedulers such as rate-monotonic, which is not common in general-purpose systems, as it requires additional information in order to schedule a task: namely, a bound or worst-case estimate for how long the task must execute.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Specific algorithms for scheduling such hard real-time tasks exist, like earliest deadline first, which, ignoring the overhead of context switching, is sufficient for system loads of less than 100%.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] New overlay scheduling systems, such as an adaptive partition scheduler assist in managing large systems with a mixture of hard real-time and non real-time applications.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] In a real-time digital signal processing (DSP) process, the analyzed (input) and generated (output) samples can be processed (or generated) continuously in the time it takes to input and output the same set of samples *independent* of the processing delay.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] It means that the processing delay must be bounded even if the processing continues for an unlimited time.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] The mean processing time per sample, including overhead, is no greater than the sampling period, which is the reciprocal of the sampling rate.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] This is the criterion whether the samples are grouped together in large segments and processed as blocks or are processed individually and whether there are long, short, or non-existent input and output buffers.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Consider an audio DSP example; if a process requires 2.01 seconds to analyze, synthesize, or process 2.00 seconds of sound, it is not real-time.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] However, if it takes 1.99 seconds, it is or can be made into a real-time DSP process.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] A common life analogy is standing in a line or queue waiting for the checkout in a grocery store.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] If the line asymptotically grows longer and longer without bound, the checkout process is not real-time.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] If the length of the line is bounded, customers are being "processed" and output as rapidly, on average, as they are being inputted, then that process *is* real-time.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] The grocer might go out of business or must at least lose business if they cannot make their checkout process real-time; thus, it is fundamentally important that this process is real-time.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] A signal processing algorithm that cannot keep up with the flow of input data, with output falling further and further behind the input, is not real-time.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] If the delay of the output (relative to the input) is bounded regarding a process that operates over an unlimited time, then that signal processing algorithm is real-time, even if the throughput delay may be very long.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Real-time signal processing is necessary, but not sufficient in and of itself, for live signal processing such as what is required in live event support.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Live audio digital signal processing requires both real-time operation and a sufficient limit to throughput delay so as to be tolerable to performers using stage monitors or in-ear monitors and not noticeable as lip sync error by the audience also directly watching the performers.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Tolerable limits to latency for live, real-time processing is a subject of investigation and debate, but is estimated to be between 6 and 20 milliseconds.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Real-time bidirectional telecommunications delays of less than 300 ms ("round trip" or twice the unidirectional delay) are considered "acceptable" to avoid undesired "talk-over" in conversation.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Real-time computing is sometimes misunderstood to be high-performance computing, but this is not an accurate classification.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] For example, a massive supercomputer executing a scientific simulation may offer impressive performance, yet it is not executing a real-time computation.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Conversely, once the hardware and software for an anti-lock braking system have been designed to meet its required deadlines, no further performance gains are obligatory or even useful.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Furthermore, if a network server is highly loaded with network traffic, its response time may be slower, but will (in most cases) still succeed before it times out (hits its deadline).
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Hence, such a network server would not be considered a real-time system: temporal failures (delays, time-outs, etc.) are typically small and compartmentalized (limited in effect), but are not catastrophic failures.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] In a real-time system, such as the FTSE 100 Index, a slowdown beyond limits would often be considered catastrophic in its application context.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] The most important requirement of a real-time system is consistent output, not high throughput.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Some kinds of software, such as many chess-playing programs, can fall into either category.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] For instance, a chess program designed to play in a tournament with a clock will need to decide on a move before a certain deadline or lose the game, and is therefore a real-time computation, but a chess program that is allowed to run indefinitely before moving is not.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] In both of these cases, however, high performance is desirable: the more work a tournament chess program can do in the allotted time, the better its moves will be, and the faster an unconstrained chess program runs, the sooner it will be able to move.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] High performance is indicative of the amount of processing that is performed in a given amount of time, whereas real-time is the ability to get done with the processing to yield a useful output in the available time.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] For example, a near-real-time display depicts an event or situation as it existed at the current time minus the processing time, as nearly the time of the live event.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] The distinction between the terms "near real time" and "real time" is somewhat nebulous and must be defined for the situation at hand.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] The term implies that there are no significant delays.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] In many cases, processing described as "real-time" would be more accurately described as "near real-time".
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Near real-time also refers to delayed real-time transmission of voice and video.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] It allows playing video images, in approximately real-time, without having to wait for an entire large video file to download.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Incompatible databases can export/import to common flat files that the other database can import/export on a scheduled basis so they can sync/share common data in "near real-time" with each other.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Several methods exist to aid the design of real-time systems, an example of which is MASCOT, an old but very successful method that represents the concurrent structure of the system.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/real-time-computing] Other examples are HOOD, Real-Time UML, AADL, the Ravenscar profile, and Real-time Java.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/stream-reservation-protocol] SRP is part of the IEEE Audio Video Bridging (AVB) and Time-Sensitive Networking (TSN) standards.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/stream-reservation-protocol] The SRP technical group started work in September 2006 and finished meetings in 2009.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/stream-reservation-protocol] SRP registers a stream and reserves the resources required through the entire path taken by the stream, based on the bandwidth requirement and the latency which are defined by a stream reservation traffic class.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/stream-reservation-protocol] Required bandwidth is calculated as MaxFrameSize × MaxIntervalFrames.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/stream-reservation-protocol] If a bridge is able to reserve the required resources, it propagates the advertisement to the next bridge; otherwise a 'talker failed' message is raised.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/stream-reservation-protocol] When the advertise message reaches the listener, it replies with 'listener ready' message that propagates back to the talker.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/stream-reservation-protocol] Talker advertise and listener ready messages can be de-registered, which terminates the stream.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/stream-reservation-protocol] Periodic polling of advertise and ready messages is used to detect unresponsive devices.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/stream-reservation-protocol] Worst case latency is recalculated at every bridge, so higher protocol layers can use it for media synchronization.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/stream-reservation-protocol] The per-port peer delay provided by gPTP and the network bridge residence delay are added to calculate the accumulated delays and ensure the latency requirement is met.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/stream-reservation-protocol] Control traffic has the third highest priority and includes gPTP and SRP traffic.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/stream-reservation-protocol] The SRP works using the Multiple MAC Registration Protocol (MMRP), the Multiple VLAN Registration Protocol (MVRP), and the Multiple Stream Registration Protocol (MSRP).
[src:time-sensitive-networking/stream-reservation-protocol] MMRP controls propagation of group registration, and MVRP controls VLAN membership (MAC address information).
[src:time-sensitive-networking/stream-reservation-protocol] MSRP works in a distributed network of bridges and end stations; it registers and advertises data streams and reserves bridge resources to provide the QoS guarantees.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/stream-reservation-protocol] A station (talker) sends a reservation request with the general MRP application.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/stream-reservation-protocol] All participants in the stream have an MSRP application and the MRP Attribute Declaration (MAD) specification for describing the stream characteristics.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/stream-reservation-protocol] Then each bridge within the same SRP domain can map, allocate, and forward the stream with the necessary resources by using the MRP attribute propagation.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The majority of projects define extensions to the IEEE 802.1Q – Bridges and Bridged Networks, which describes virtual LANs and network switches.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] These extensions in particular address transmission with very low latency and high availability.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Applications include converged networks with real-time audio/video streaming and real-time control streams which are used in automotive applications and industrial control facilities.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Standard information technology network equipment has no concept of "time" and cannot provide synchronization and precision timing.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Delivering data reliably is more important than delivering within a specific time, so there are no constraints on delay or synchronization precision.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Even if the average hop delay is very low, individual delays can be unacceptably high.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Network congestion is handled by throttling and retransmitting dropped packets at the transport layer, but there are no means to prevent congestion at the link layer.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Data can be lost when the buffers are too small or the bandwidth is insufficient, but excessive buffering adds to the delay, which is unacceptable when low deterministic delays are required.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The different AVB/TSN standards documents specified by IEEE 802.1 can be grouped into three basic key component categories that are required for a complete real-time communication solution based on switched Ethernet networks with deterministic quality of service (QoS) for point-to-point connections.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Each and every standard specification can be used on its own and is mostly self-sufficient.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] However, only when used together in a concerted way, can TSN achieve its full potential as a communication system.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The IEEE AVB/TSN suite serves as the foundation for deterministic networking to satisfy the common requirements of these applications.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] AVB/TSN can handle rate-constrained traffic, where each stream has a bandwidth limit defined by minimum inter-frame intervals and maximal frame size, and time-trigger traffic with an exact accurate time to be sent.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Low-priority traffic is passed on a best-effort basis, with no timing and delivery guarantees.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] In contrast to standard Ethernet according to IEEE 802.3 and Ethernet bridging according to IEEE 802.1Q, time is very important in TSN networks.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] For real-time communication with hard, non-negotiable time boundaries for end-to-end transmission latencies, all devices in this network need to have a common time reference and therefore, need to synchronize their clocks among each other.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] This is not only true for the end devices of a communication stream, such as an industrial controller and a manufacturing robot, but also true for network components, such as Ethernet switches.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Only through synchronized clocks is it possible for all network devices to operate in unison and execute the required operation at exactly the required point in time.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Although time synchronization in TSN networks can be achieved with GPS clock, this is costly and there is no guarantee that the endpoint device has access to the radio or satellite signal at all times.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Due to these constraints, time in TSN networks is usually distributed from one central time source directly through the network itself using the IEEE 1588 Precision Time Protocol, which utilizes Ethernet frames to distribute time synchronization information.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1AS is a tightly constrained subset of IEEE 1588 with sub-microsecond precision and extensions to support synchronisation over WiFi radio (IEEE 802.11).
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The idea behind this profile is to narrow the huge list of different IEEE 1588 options down to a manageable few critical options that are applicable to home networks or networks in automotive or industrial automation environments.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1AS-2011 defines the Generalized Precision Time Protocol (gPTP) profile which, like all profiles of IEEE 1588, selects among the options of 1588, but also generalizes the architecture to allow PTP to apply beyond wired Ethernet networks.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] These calculated delays are then referenced to the GrandMaster (GM) clock in a bridge elected by the Best Master Clock Algorithm, a clock Spanning Tree Protocol to which all Clock Master (CM) and endpoint devices attempt to synchronize.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Any device that does not synchronize to timing messages is outside of the timing domain boundaries (Figure 2).
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Synchronization accuracy depends on precise measurements of link delay and frame residence time.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] 802.1AS uses *logical syntonization*, where a ratio between local clock and GM clock frequencies is used to calculate synchronized time, and a ratio between local and GM clock frequencies to calculate propagation delay.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE802.1AS-2020 introduces improved time measurement accuracy and support for multiple time domains for redundancy.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Scheduling and traffic shaping allow for the coexistence of different traffic classes with different priorities on the same network – each with different requirements for available bandwidth and end-to-end latency.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Traffic shaping refers to the process of distributing frames/packets evenly in time to smooth out the traffic.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Without traffic shaping at sources and bridges, the packets will *bunch*, i.e., agglomerate into bursts of traffic, overwhelming the buffers in subsequent bridges/switches along the path.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Standard bridging according to IEEE 802.1Q uses a strict priority scheme with eight distinct priorities.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] On the protocol level, these priorities are visible in the Priority Code Point (PCP) field in the 802.1Q VLAN tag of a standard Ethernet frame.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] These priorities already distinguish between more important and less important network traffic, but even with the highest of the eight priorities, no absolute guarantee for an end-to-end delivery time can be given.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The reason for this is buffering effects inside the Ethernet switches.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] If a switch has started the transmission of an Ethernet frame on one of its ports, even the highest-priority frame has to wait inside the switch buffer for this transmission to finish.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] With standard Ethernet switching, this nondeterminism cannot be avoided.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] This is not an issue in environments where applications do not depend on the timely delivery of single Ethernet frames - such as office IT infrastructures.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] In these environments, file transfers, emails or other business applications have limited time sensitivity themselves and are usually protected by other mechanisms further up the protocol stack, such as the Transmission Control Protocol.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] In industrial automation (Programmable Logic Controller (PLC) with an industrial robot) and automotive car environments, where closed loop control or safety applications are using the Ethernet network, reliable and timely delivery is of utmost importance.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] AVB/TSN enhances standard Ethernet communication by adding mechanisms to provide different time slices for different traffic classes and ensure timely delivery with soft and hard real-time requirements of control system applications.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The mechanism of utilizing the eight distinct VLAN priorities is retained, to ensure complete backward compatibility to non-TSN Ethernet.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Time-sensitive traffic has several priority classes.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] For credit-based shaper 802.1Qav, Stream Reservation Class A is the highest priority with a transmission period of 125 μs; Class B has the second-highest priority with a maximum transmission period of 250 μs.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Traffic classes shall not exceed their preconfigured maximum bandwidth (75% for audio and video applications).
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The worst-case latency requirement is defined as 2 ms for Class A and 50 ms for Class B, but has been shown to be unreliable.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Control traffic has the third-highest priority and includes gPTP and SRP traffic.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Time-aware scheduler 802.1Qbv introduces Class CDT for real-time control data from sensors and command streams to actuators, with worst-case latency of 100 μs over 5 hops, and a maximum transmission period of 0.5 ms.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Class CDT takes the highest priority over classes A, B, and control traffic.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1Qav Forwarding and Queuing Enhancements for Time-Sensitive Streams defines traffic shaping using priority classes, which is based on a simple form of leaky bucket credit-based fair queuing.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] 802.1Qav is designed to reduce buffering in receiving bridges and endpoints.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The credit-based shaper defines credits in bits for two separate queues, dedicated to Class A and Class B traffic.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Thus the idleSlope is the bandwidth reserved for the queue by the bridge, and the sendSlope is the transmission rate of the port MAC service.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] If the credit is negative and no frames are transmitted, credit increases at *idleSlope* rate until zero is reached.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] If an AVB frame cannot be transmitted because a non-AVB frame is in transmission, credit accumulates at *idleSlope* rate, but positive credit is allowed.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Additional limits hiCredit and loCredit are derived from the maximum frame size and maximum interference size, the idleSlope/sendSlope, and the maximum port transmission rate.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Reserved AV stream traffic frames are forwarded with high priority over non-reserved best-effort traffic, subject to credit-based traffic shaping rules which may require them to wait for a certain amount of credits.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] This protects best-effort traffic by limiting the maximum AV stream burst.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The frames are scheduled very evenly, though only on an aggregate basis, to smooth out the delivery times and reduce bursting and bunching, which can lead to buffer overflows and packet drops that trigger retransmissions.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The increased buffering delay makes re-transmitted packets obsolete by the time they arrive, resulting in frame drops, which reduces the quality of AV applications.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Deriving guaranteed upper bounds on delays in TSN is non-trivial and is currently being researched, e.g., by using the mathematical framework Network Calculus.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1Qat Stream Reservation Protocol (SRP) is a distributed peer-to-peer protocol that specifies admission controls based on resource requirements of the flow and available network resources.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] SRP reserves resources and advertises streams from the sender/source (talker) to the receivers/destinations (listeners); it works to satisfy QoS requirements for each stream and guarantee the availability of sufficient network resources along the entire flow transmission path.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The traffic streams are identified and registered with a 64-bit *StreamID*, made up of the 48-bit MAC address (EUI) and 16-bit *UniqueID* to identify different streams from the same source.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] SRP employs variants of Multiple Registration Protocol (MRP) to register and de-register attribute values on switches/bridges/devices - the Multiple MAC Registration Protocol (MMRP), the Multiple VLAN Registration Protocol (MVRP), and the Multiple Stream Registration Protocol (MSRP).
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Resources are allocated and configured in both the end nodes of the data stream and the transit nodes along the data flow path, with an end-to-end signaling mechanism to detect the success/failure.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Worst-case latency is calculated by querying every bridge.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Reservation requests use the general MRP application with the MRP attribute propagation mechanism.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] All nodes along the flow path pass the MRP Attribute Declaration (MAD) specification, which describes the stream characteristics so that bridges could allocate the necessary resources.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] If a bridge is able to reserve the required resources, it propagates the advertisement to the next bridge; otherwise, a *talker failed* message is raised.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] When the advertisement message reaches the listener, it replies with *listener ready* message that propagates back to the talker.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Successful reservation is only guaranteed when all intermediate nodes support SRP and respond to advertise and ready messages; in Figure 2 above, AVB domain 1 is unable to connect with AVB domain 2.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] SRP uses a decentralized registration and reservation procedure; multiple requests can introduce delays for critical traffic.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1Qcc-2018 "Stream Reservation Protocol (SRP) Enhancements and Performance Improvements" amendment reduces the size of reservation messages and redefines timers so they trigger updates only when link state or reservation is changed.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] CNC implements a per-stream request-response model, where SR class is not explicitly used: end-stations send requests for a specific stream (via edge port) without knowledge of the network configuration, and CNC performs stream reservation centrally.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] MSRP only runs on the link to end-stations as an information carrier between CNC and end-stations, not for stream reservation.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Centralized User Configuration (CUC) is an optional node that discovers end stations, their capabilities and user requirements, and configures delay-optimized TSN features (for closed-loop IACS applications).
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Seamless interop with Resource Reservation Protocol (RSVP) transport is provided.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] 802.1Qcc allows centralized configuration management to coexist with decentralized, fully distributed configuration of the SRP protocol, and also supports hybrid configurations for legacy AVB devices.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] 802.1Qcc can be combined with IEEE 802.1Qca Path Control and Reservation (PCR) and TSN traffic shapers.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] While the 802.1Qav FQTSS/CBS works very well with soft real-time traffic, worst-case delays are both hop count and network topology dependent.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Pathological topologies introduce delays, so buffer size requirements have to consider network topology.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] CQF can be used with the IEEE 802.1Qbv time-aware scheduler, IEEE 802.1Qbu frame preemption, and IEEE 802.1Qci ingress traffic policing.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1Qci Per-Stream Filtering and Policing (PSFP) improves network robustness by filtering individual traffic streams.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] It prevents traffic overload conditions that may affect bridges and the receiving endpoints due to malfunction or Denial of Service (DoS) attacks.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The stream filter uses rule matching to allow frames with specified stream IDs and priority levels and apply policy actions otherwise.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] All streams are coordinated at their gates, similarly to the 802.1Qch signaling.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The flow metering applies predefined bandwidth profiles for each stream.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The IEEE 802.1Qbv time-aware scheduler is designed to separate the communication on the Ethernet network into fixed length, repeating time cycles.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Within these cycles, different time slices can be configured that can be assigned to one or several of the eight Ethernet priorities.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] By doing this, it is possible to grant exclusive use - for a limited time - to the Ethernet transmission medium for those traffic classes that need transmission guarantees and can't be interrupted.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The basic concept is a time-division multiple access (TDMA) scheme.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] By establishing virtual communication channels for specific time periods, time-critical communication can be separated from non-critical background traffic.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Time-aware scheduler introduces Stream Reservation Class CDT for time-critical control data, with worst-case latency of 100 μs over 5 hops, and maximum transmission period of 0.5 ms, in addition to classes A and B defined for IEEE 802.1Qav credit-based traffic shaper.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] By granting exclusive access to the transmission medium and devices to time-critical traffic classes, the buffering effects in the Ethernet switch transmission buffers can be avoided and time-critical traffic can be transmitted without non-deterministic interruptions.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] In this example, each cycle consists of two time slices.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Time slice 1 only allows the transmission of traffic tagged with VLAN priority 3, and time slice 2 in each cycle allows for the rest of the priorities to be sent.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Since the IEEE 802.1Qbv scheduler requires all clocks on all network devices (Ethernet switches and end devices) to be synchronized and the identical schedule to be configured, all devices understand which priority can be sent to the network at any given point in time.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Since time slice 2 has more than one priority assigned to it, within this time slice, the priorities are handled according to standard IEEE 802.1Q strict priority scheduling.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] This separation of Ethernet transmissions into cycles and time slices can be enhanced further by the inclusion of other scheduling or traffic shaping algorithms, such as the IEEE 802.1Qav credit-based traffic shaper.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] In this particular example, IEEE 802.1Qav could be assigned to one or two of the priorities that are used in time slice two to distinguish further between audio/video traffic and background file transfers.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The Time-Sensitive Networking Task Group specifies a number of different schedulers and traffic shapers that can be combined to achieve the nonreactive coexistence of hard real-time, soft real-time and background traffic on the same Ethernet infrastructure.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] When an Ethernet interface has started the transmission of a frame to the transmission medium, this transmission has to be completely finished before another transmission can take place.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] This includes the transmission of the CRC-32 checksum at the end of the frame to ensure a reliable, fault-free transmission.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] This inherent property of Ethernet networks - again- poses a challenge to the TDMA approach of the IEEE 802.1Qbv scheduler.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Just before the end of time slice 2 in cycle n, a new frame transmission is started.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Unfortunately, this frame is too large to fit into its time slice.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Since the transmission of this frame cannot be interrupted, the frame infringes the following time slice 1 of the next cycle n+1.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] By partially or completely blocking a time-critical time slice, real-time frames can be delayed up to the point where they cannot meet the application requirements any longer.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] This is very similar to the actual buffering effects that happen in non-TSN Ethernet switches, so TSN has to specify a mechanism to prevent this from happening.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The IEEE 802.1Qbv time-aware scheduler has to ensure that the Ethernet interface is not busy with the transmission of a frame when the scheduler changes from one time slice to the next.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The time-aware scheduler achieves this by putting a guard band in front of every time slice that carries time-critical traffic.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] During this guard band time, no new Ethernet frame transmission may be started; only already ongoing transmissions may be finished.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The duration of this guard band has to be as long as it takes the maximum frame size to be safely transmitted.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The total time needed for sending this frame is dependent on the link speed of the Ethernet network.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] In this case, the guard band has to be at least 123.36 μs long.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] With the guard band, the total bandwidth or time that is usable within a time slice is reduced by the length of the guard band.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Note: to facilitate the presentation of the topic, the actual size of the guard band in figure 3 is not to scale, but is significantly smaller than indicated by the frame in figure 2.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] In this example, the time slice 1 always contains high-priority data (e.g. for motion control), while time slice 2 always contains best-effort data.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Therefore, a guard band needs to be placed at every transition point into time slice 1 to protect the time slice of the critical data stream(s).
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] To partially mitigate the loss of bandwidth through the guard band, the standard IEEE 802.1Qbv includes a length-aware scheduling mechanism.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] This mechanism is used when store-and-forward switching is utilized: after the full reception of an Ethernet frame that needs to be transmitted on a port where the guard band is in effect, the scheduler checks the overall length of the frame.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] If the frame can fit completely inside the guard band, without any infringement of the following high-priority slice, the scheduler can send this frame, despite an active guard band, and reduce the waste of bandwidth.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] This mechanism, however, cannot be used when cut-through switching is enabled, since the total length of the Ethernet frame needs to be known a priori.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Therefore, when cut-through switching is used to minimize end-to-end latency, the waste of bandwidth will still occur.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Also, this does not help with the minimum achievable cycle time.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Therefore, length-aware scheduling is an improvement, but cannot mitigate all drawbacks that are introduced by the guard band.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] To further mitigate the negative effects of the guard bands, the IEEE working groups 802.1 and 802.3 have specified the frame pre-emption technology.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The two working groups collaborated in this endeavour since the technology required both changes in the Ethernet Media Access Control (MAC) scheme that is under the control of IEEE 802.3, as well as changes in the management mechanisms that are under the control of IEEE 802.1.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Due to this fact, frame pre-emption is described in two different standards documents: IEEE 802.1Qbu for the bridge management component and IEEE 802.3br for the Ethernet MAC component.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Frame preemption defines two MAC services for an egress port: preemptable MAC (pMAC) and express MAC (eMAC).
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Express frames can interrupt the transmission of preemptable frames.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] On resume, MAC merge sublayer reassembles frame fragments in the next bridge.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Preemption causes computational overhead in the link interface, as the operational context shall be transitioned to the express frame.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Figure 4 gives a basic example how frame pre-emption works.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] During the process of sending a best effort Ethernet frame, the MAC interrupts the frame transmission just before the start of the guard band.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The partial frame is completed with a CRC and will be stored in the next switch to wait for the second part of the frame to arrive.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] After the high-priority traffic in time slice 1 has passed and the cycle switches back to time slice 2, the interrupted frame transmission is resumed.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Frame pre-emption always operates on a pure link-by-link basis and only fragments from one Ethernet switch to the next Ethernet switch, where the frame is reassembled.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] In contrast to fragmentation with the Internet Protocol (IP), no end-to-end fragmentation is supported.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Each partial frame is completed by a CRC-32 for error detection.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] In contrast to the regular Ethernet CRC-32, the last 16 bits are inverted to make a partial frame distinguishable from a regular Ethernet frame.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] In addition, the start of frame delimiter (SFD) is changed.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The support for frame pre-emption has to be activated on each link between devices individually.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] To signal the capability for frame pre-emption on a link, an Ethernet switch announces this capability through the LLDP (Link Layer Discovery Protocol).
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] When a device receives such an LLDP announcement on a network port and supports frame pre-emption itself, it may activate the capability.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] There is no direct negotiation and activation of the capability on adjacent devices.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Any device that receives the LLDP pre-emption announcement assumes that on the other end of the link, a device is present that can understand the changes in the frame format (changed CRC-32 and SFD).
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Frame pre-emption allows for a significant reduction of the guard band.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The length of the guard band is now dependent on the precision of the frame pre-emption mechanism: how small is the minimum size of the frame that the mechanism can still preempt.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.3br specifies the best accuracy for this mechanism at 64 bytes – due to the fact that this is the minimum size of a still valid Ethernet frame.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] In this case, the guard band can be reduced to a total of 127 bytes: 64 bytes (minimum frame) + 63 bytes (remaining length that cannot be pre-empted).
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] All larger frames can be pre-empted again and therefore, there is no need to protect against this size with a guard band.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] This minimizes the best effort bandwidth that is lost and also allows for much shorter cycle times at slower Ethernet speeds, such as 100 Mbit/s and below.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Since the pre-emption takes place in hardware in the MAC, as the frame passes through, cut-through switching can be supported as well, since the overall frame size is not needed a priori.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The MAC interface just checks in regular 64-byte intervals whether the frame needs to be preempted or not.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The combination of time synchronization, the IEEE 802.1Qbv scheduler and frame pre-emption already constitutes an effective set of standards that can be utilized to guarantee the coexistence of different traffic categories on a network while also providing end-to-end latency guarantees.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] This will be enhanced further as new IEEE 802.1 specifications, such as 802.1Qch are finalized.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Overall, the time-aware scheduler has high implementation complexity and its use of bandwidth is not efficient.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Task and event scheduling in endpoints has to be coupled with the gate scheduling of the traffic shaper in order to lower the latencies.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] A critical shortcoming is that some delay is incurred when an endpoint streams unsynchronized data, due to the waiting time for the next time-triggered window.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The time-aware scheduler requires tight synchronization of its time-triggered windows, so all bridges on the stream path must be synchronized.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] However, synchronizing TSN bridge frame selection and transmission time is nontrivial even in moderately sized networks and requires a fully managed solution.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Frame preemption is hard to implement and has not seen wide industry support.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Credit-based, time-aware and cyclic (peristaltic) shapers require network-wide coordinated time and utilize network bandwidth inefficiently, as they enforce packet transmission at periodic cycles.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The IEEE 802.1Qcr Asynchronous Traffic Shaper (ATS) operates asynchronously based on local clocks in each bridge, improving link utilization for mixed traffic types, such as periodic with arbitrary periods, sporadic (event driven), and rate-constrained.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] ATS employs the urgency-based scheduler (UBS), which prioritizes urgent traffic using per-class queuing and per-stream reshaping.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Asynchronicity is achieved by interleaved shaping with traffic characterization based on Token Bucket Emulation, a token bucket emulation model, to eliminate the burstiness cascade effects of per-class shaping.
[src:time-sensitive-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The TBE shaper controls the traffic by average transmission rate, but allows a certain level of burst traffic.
